{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f5b7c2b6-b2ad-46b8-91ac-d3cdd511113c","content":"Here's what's happening and how to fix it:\n\n## Why CLI builds are slower\n\nVisual Studio keeps an in-process MSBuild host alive, avoiding JIT startup and project re-evaluation. Each `dotnet build` invocation pays that cost fresh.\n\n## Recommendations (most to least impactful)\n\n### 1. Use `dotnet watch` for inner-loop development\n```bash\ndotnet watch build\n```\nKeeps the build host alive and rebuilds on file changes — eliminates startup overhead entirely.\n\n### 2. Enable the MSBuild Server (.NET 8 opt-in, default in .NET 9)\n```bash\nexport DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1\ndotnet build\n```\nReuses a long-lived MSBuild process across CLI invocations, similar to how VS works.\n\n### 3. Skip restore when packages haven't changed\n```bash\ndotnet build --no-restore\n```\nThe implicit `dotnet restore` on every build adds ~0.5–1s of overhead even when nothing changed.\n\n### 4. Combine flags for fastest one-shot builds\n```bash\nexport DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1\ndotnet build --no-restore --tl\n```\n\nThe single biggest win is **`dotnet watch`** for edit-build-test cycles, or enabling the **MSBuild server** if you prefer explicit `dotnet build` calls. No project file changes needed — these are all CLI/environment switches.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b4b8a2d2-c0ca-4751-83f2-3eabb76be3a0","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The developer reports that `dotnet build` from the CLI is slow for incremental builds (2-4 seconds even when nothing changed), while Visual Studio builds are nearly instant. They've already verified that analyzers aren't the issue and incremental build targets work correctly. The overhead comes from MSBuild process startup and re-evaluation.\n\nThe key insight here is that Visual Studio uses an MSBuild server process that stays warm between builds, avoiding the JIT and project evaluation overhead on each invocation. The `dotnet build` CLI, by default, spawns a new MSBuild process each time.\n\nThe solution is to use the **MSBuild Server** (also known as the MSBuild build server or `dotnet build-server`). \n\nStarting with .NET 8, MSBuild has a server mode that keeps the process alive between builds, mirroring Visual Studio's approach. To enable it, set the environment variable `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1` before running `dotnet build`, which will reuse the warm MSBuild process and eliminate the startup overhead.\n\nFor the development workflow, `dotnet watch build` is the most impactful optimization—it keeps the build process running and watches for file changes, triggering incremental rebuilds automatically. I should also mention that adding `--no-restore` to subsequent builds skips the NuGet restore step when dependencies haven't changed, further reducing build time. I'm narrowing down to the most reliable options available in .NET 8: enabling the MSBuild server, using `dotnet watch` for development, and skipping restore when dependencies haven't changed—these are the concrete levers that actually reduce build times without requiring project-specific configuration.","outputTokens":1259},"id":"ac3c9269-54a6-40c4-a1e9-c63cb9aa08e1","timestamp":"2026-04-08T00:52:45.730Z","parentId":"3f8896f0-7c3a-4e16-bcc0-9df045d523ed"}
